The article discusses various reports highlighting the positive state of the American economy. The Bureau of Labor Statistics announced the addition of 313,000 new jobs in February, surpassing expectations and maintaining the unemployment rate at an 18-year low of 4.1 percent. Small businesses are also raising wages to attract and retain employees, particularly in the construction, manufacturing, transportation, and communication industries. U.S. consumer confidence is at a 17-year high due to optimism about employment prospects and increased income from recent tax cuts. Furthermore, the International Energy Agency predicts that the U.S. will become the largest oil producer in the world by 2023, surpassing Russia. The Federal Reserve's beige book shows evidence of wage growth across the country, indicating a tight labor market. The Institute for Supply Management reported that the manufacturing index reached its highest level since May 2004, indicating improving conditions. Real disposable incomes in the U.S. increased by 0.6 percent in January, the largest gain since April 2015, due to recent tax cuts. Finally, private-sector employment remained strong in February, with the addition of 235,000 jobs.